                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d248">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">863.48/119: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Carroll</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="7" xml:id="d248fn7">Via the Embassy at Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-02-12T12:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 12, 1920—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received February 16—1:01 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>33. Alluding today to the contents of the Department’s telegram no. 6, February
                    6, 3 p.m. The Acting Minister of Foreign Affairs <pb facs="0356" n="258"
                        xml:id="pg_258"/> informed me that his Government feels that its attitude
                    towards Austria has been unintentionally misrepresented and that it is now
                    preparing a statement of its position which, upon completion, he will submit to
                    me for transmission to the Department. …</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carroll</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
